<h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;">1. Overview of Primary Education</h1>
Primary education in Singapore is a fundamental component of the country's education system. It covers six years of schooling, typically starting at age 6 and ending at age 12. Primary education is compulsory for all Singaporean children.</br>

<br><h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;"> 2. Structure and Curriculum</h1>

The primary school curriculum is designed to provide students with a solid foundation in essential skills and knowledge. It is divided into the following levels:

<ol>
<br><li>Primary 1 (P1) to Primary 6 (P6): </li>
<li>Primary 1 and 2: Focus on building fundamental skills in English, Mathematics, and Mother Tongue languages (such as Mandarin, Malay, or Tamil).</li>
<li>Primary 3 and 4: Introduction of Science and Social Studies, along with continued development in English, Mathematics, and Mother Tongue.</li>
<li>Primary 5 and 6: Preparation for the Primary School Leaving Examination (PSLE), which determines the student's placement in secondary school.</li></ol>

<br><h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;">3. Core Subjects</h1>
English Language: Emphasis on reading, writing, listening, and speaking skills.
Mathematics: Focus on numeracy, problem-solving, and logical reasoning.
Mother Tongue Language: Learning of Singapore’s official languages, which include Mandarin, Malay, and Tamil.
Science: Introduction to basic scientific concepts and inquiry skills.
Social Studies: Understanding of Singapore's history, culture, and geography.</br>
<br><h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;">4. Holistic Education</h1>
Singapore's primary schools aim to foster not just academic excellence but also character development, creativity, and physical well-being. The curriculum includes:

Art and Music: Encouraging creativity and artistic expression.
Physical Education: Promoting physical fitness and teamwork.
Civics and Moral Education: Instilling values and citizenship.</br>

<br><h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;">5. Assessment and Examinations</h1>
Formative Assessments: Regular quizzes, assignments, and class participation are used to monitor and support students' learning progress.
Summative Assessments: Includes mid-year and end-of-year exams.
Primary School Leaving Examination (PSLE): A national examination taken at the end of Primary 6, which determines the student's future academic path.</br>

<br><h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;">6. School Environment</h1>
Primary schools in Singapore are equipped with modern facilities and resources to support learning. Schools often have well-maintained classrooms, libraries, science labs, and sports facilities. They also offer co-curricular activities (CCAs) to help students develop additional skills and interests.</br>

<br><h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;">7. Parental Involvement</h1>
Parents are encouraged to be actively involved in their child’s education through regular communication with teachers, participation in school events, and supporting learning at home.</br>

<br><h1 style="color:firebrick; font-size: 25px;">8. Diversity and Inclusivity</h1>
Singapore's primary schools cater to a diverse population, with programs in place to support students from different backgrounds and with varying needs. This includes provisions for students with special educational needs.</br>
